You are implementing the global CSS stylesheet (`app/globals.css`) for a video production pipeline editor built with Next.js 15 and Tailwind CSS v4. This file uses the Tailwind v4 CSS-first configuration approach with `@import 'tailwindcss'` and an `@theme {}` block â€” no `tailwind.config.js` needed.

Requirements
1. Use `@import 'tailwindcss'` at the top (Tailwind v4 CSS-first syntax).
2. Define an `@theme {}` block with custom color tokens for the pipeline editor UI:
   - Sidebar background: `--color-sidebar: #0f172a` (dark slate)
   - Stage status badge colors: `--color-stage-done: #22c55e`, `--color-stage-running: #f59e0b`, `--color-stage-error: #ef4444`, `--color-stage-not-started: #64748b`
   - Annotation severity: `--color-severity-critical: #ef4444`, `--color-severity-major: #f97316`, `--color-severity-minor: #eab308`, `--color-severity-pass: #22c55e`
   - Panel background: `--color-panel: #1e293b`
   - Border: `--color-border: #334155`
3. Define `@layer base` with dark body defaults: `body { background-color: theme(--color-panel); color: #e2e8f0; font-family: ui-monospace, 'Cascadia Code', monospace; }`.
4. Define `@layer base` styles for scrollbars (webkit): thin scrollbars with panel background track and border-color thumb.
5. Define utility classes for the SSE log panel: monospace font, small text, no wrapping.
6. No `tailwind.config.js` â€” all configuration is in this CSS file via `@theme {}`.

